More than a third of children between 9 and 13 have problems with overweight, with 9 percent of all students and 5 percent of all children being overweight.
Recent surveys have shown that adipose children mostly come from families with unhealthy lifestyles.
Once again, it shows how important for a person’s healthy development is the environment in which he grows up and the examples that surround him.
On the tables of adipose children, sausages are up to half as common on the table as in families where normal weight children live.
More than 19 percent of overweight children had apples for dinner the day before the educational campaign under the motto "Adipositas is no coincidence".
In families with dicks, sport is not just one of their favorite occupations, but also the majority of today’s students – only 15 percent responded that their parents find time for active exercise at least once a week.
Survey of 900 children
The survey took place last year towards the end of the school year, during which almost 900 children from primary schools were surveyed throughout the Czech Republic.
This was already the second year of the action "Adipositas is no coincidence", which is supported by the General Health Fund and the company Unilever.
To date, more than 12 thousand students from 4th and 8th grades have participated in the project.
Unhealthy diet and lack of exercise in the family are crucial factors that are responsible for the alarmingly increasing number of overweight or even obese children.
“Only half of the children surveyed, for example, had five times a day, in the breakfast-second breakfast-breakfast-vesper-dinner mode – one of the main prerequisites for a healthy diet,” one of the survey results reads.
No breakfast and sausage for dinner
Experts point out that even relative small things, such as the family’s regular breakfast time, are important for a child’s healthy development.
In the Czech Republic, however, only 23 percent of the students’ families have breakfast.
And - in most families, everyone has breakfast on their own.
The worst was the finding that is not breakfast at all in every tenth family.
Breakfast is considered to be the cornerstone of a healthy daily diet.
Among other things, the survey showed that unhealthy apples are consumed much more often in families of overweight children.
And almost everyone – regardless of weight – drinks sweet lemonade every day (70 percent)
While more than 40 percent of the children surveyed do sports, only less than half of their parents do so – only 15 percent.
Set up your own menu
Another part of the survey allowed selected children (204 boys and 172 girls from 13 schools) to come up with their own meal plan from offered options according to appetite and opinion.
“What Czech children prefer between 12 and 15 in terms of nutrition is far from the ideal of a healthy diet.
Among their favorite foods were many flour dishes, meat dishes and, of course, sweet foods.
"Especially alarming is the great popularity of sweet lemonade," the final report emphasizes on this survey.
At lunch, that is, the main dish, the doughnuts almost won in front of the poultry.
The children almost did not like herring and the popularity of fish and vegetable dishes as lunch was very low.
Approaching to Health
At the same time, the survey also showed that children are quite willing to change their eating habits if they get the right information.
"In the control group of survey participants who completed the questionnaire after the conclusion of the exploratory lecture "Adipositas is not a coincidence", in many cases a significant shift in preferences towards principles of healthy eating was noted in the results of the project.
This was evident, for example, in the sweet limos, where many children began to give priority to ordinary water.
In the questionnaire, the children also crossed much more often poultry or fish as the main dish of the day and were willing to eat fewer noodles or sweet foods.
