V Need for Speed: "The Run" - the illegal race across America
Reviewer
The original carefree ride is made by a series of completely avoidable, dilettant mistakes for the routine ride to the early layer.
While it did manage to fulfill the ambitions for the most part, what good is that even if obviously no one wanted to do a little more.
Even before he came to the shop tables, the new part with the subtitle "The Run" raised high expectations.
However, he promised to move the already-defunct "Need for Speed" game series back into a new dimension, and in the playable demonstration examples, he actually didn't seem to be just one of many action racing games.
We were also curious as to how the adapted passages fall out, in which the main protagonist rises from the car and continues on foot.
But as you are used to at NFS, in the end, it’s a lot different than you expected.
Sure - potentially it's quite decent arcade racing, but overall the game is tempered by some superfluous mistakes that have been present in this series for more or less a few years already.
So it’s actually no longer a mistake, but rather a sign of a basically incomprehensible foulness of the game developers.
The adventure starts very well.
For the first time, one is introduced to the story, whose main character Jack has certain problems of a personal nature; the only solution seems to be to participate in an illegal race across America.
In San Francisco, so on the west coast, you get on the steering wheel - with the task of being the first in New York.
The basic idea includes a number of interesting elements.
The entire route is divided into ten stages and more than fifty individual races.
This means that each race is held on a different route and that the individual stages take place in a different, sufficiently different and interesting environment.
One does not have the impression that the game would always offer the same thing.
Some environments are still quite nice to look at, although the technical level of the graphics does not go beyond that of the previous parts of the series.
So nothing world-moving.
But the ride through the desert, through autumnal landscape or high up through deep snowy landscape seems visually very pleasant.
Over and over again, unusual elements bring a little variation in the individual races.
In the desert, for example, one is surprised by a desert storm, which greatly restricts sight.
In the mountains, you have to be absolutely careful not to be smothered by an avalanche.
In addition, the individual races are installed quite well behind each other.
Only a few, but they are enough.
For a while you try to overtake the prescribed number of opponents (in principle a classic race), then you have time to pick up (classic race against the stopwatch), then you expect another personal duel with a single opponent.
And the police are also involved, who want to mess up the whole thing.
A novelty are passages where Jack leaves the car.
It’s more about some interactive animations where Jack escapes from someone and where the player has to help him by pressing the right button at the right moment.
So nothing complicated.
However, it is surprising that there are far fewer such passages in the game than one would expect (specifically only three).
Ultimately, this is more of an advantage, because so this element has at least no chance of getting bored - it belongs in the context of the above mentioned elements that make the game more varied.
The driving model steps into the footsteps of the previous parts.
That is, from today’s point of view, although it does not tear out trees, on the other hand, one could not claim that it would be bad.
If you are looking for realistic simulations, you need to look elsewhere.
But an action-packed race will continue to suit the local driving model quite well, although one could find better in the competition.
Until then, everything is in the best order.
Real problems only appear after a certain period of time.
Unlike the driving model, the collision model is not quite O.K.
From a game of this kind it is hardly to be expected that it calculates complicated deformations and collisions, but if you have virtually no idea how the car behaves, then obviously not everything is fine.
Typical example: When passing or passing through the cars you "strip" in some places the other car only easily, but in other situations, almost identical, you get into the loop and turn wild pirouettes.
Or drive the cart straight to scrap.
Thanks to the restart system, it doesn’t matter, it’s all annoying.
The restarts are solved as follows: if you have total damage or land far away from the track, then one throws the game back to the last point of entry of the track.
Only - in each race you only have five restarts.
Once you’ve exhausted them, everything goes from the front.
So the restarts are more like a tool, in case something doesn’t work out, but you shouldn’t rely on it.
But sometimes it doesn’t even help the restart, there’s nothing else that helps to learn the critical section from the head.
It is extremely unpleasant that the same things often happen in the same places.
For example, some curves need to be traversed in a very specific way, otherwise you simply do not fit through.
Elsewhere you meet at the appropriate place "civil" cars always in the same configuration, whether you come first or fifth, five seconds earlier or a minute later.
This is especially annoying in situations when you see that the counterparty passes in front of a playing on two opposing cars, but until you get there yourself, the cars are already in such a position that you have to drive or brake them.
And it doesn’t matter when you get there, everything is designed so that it always comes close to your nose.
Contractors have other advantages.
Throughout the game, there are a few places where you are always taken over by the same opponent at the same place and also here again regardless of the time.
The craziest thing is to finish the game on the long bridge, which you pass in the opposite direction.
The contractor must obviously get one out of here on the devil.
And if he is in front of one, then he takes the view of one of course, so you start there your own car a few times in Klump.
Sure - you just want to make the game more exciting and exciting but this intention is so clear that it quickly loses the joy of the game.
And that’s a shame, because despite a simpler driving model, the game is overall quite entertaining and quite loaded with action, so you almost don’t know where one of the heads is anymore.
And in principle, it doesn't matter what "guilty" is - the concept of fifty unique routes, the arrangement of races in a way that can't be tolerated, or something quite different...
An unusual idea is also the car change in the course of the races.
You should not miss the petrol stations on the route, because here you can change the car, although in most cases the car you just have is enough.
The cars are divided into three categories.
The sports cars are well suited for urban areas, the strong American limousines for straight highways and exotic super sports cars for technical rides, for example on the mountain Serpentines.
Hand in hand with the game history mode also goes the task mode (challenges) - i.e. the races in the individual locations known from the story.
Here there are not only medals, but also experience points for own profile, which is common for tasks (challenges) and history.
To get to the higher level of the driver, different objects have to be opened: from the car to the background for the profile.
This is simultaneously associated with the online Autolog function, which compares its own results with those of other players and also provides other collective functions.
One of the other incomprehensible scissors is a situation in the final race of history.
Here you get by car into a subway tunnel (my way), where in the dark you rest on the rails for a long time (my way).
On the tacho, numbers between 150 and 200 km/h (meetings), but there comes at once from behind a subway and drives an uncompromising to scrap.
In our editorial board, we will probably be arguing for a long time about whether that was a blackout of the game designers or whether the authors think us so stupid.
The technical side is nothing overwhelming but at least the overall visual impression is in most cases quite appealing and here and there even brilliant.
All the more annoying is that at some exciting moments, the image repeat frequency becomes slower and this sometimes becomes quite dramatic.
However, this is particularly true of accidents involving a larger number of participants, where a continuous FPS is of no use anyway.
The sound reproduction is O.K. and the soundtrack is a matter of taste.
In an effort to appeal to as wide a scale as possible to a more youthful audience, a soundtrack a la was created "of everything" - but who buys such a game already because of the music?!
The overall impression of Need for Speed: The Run? The feelings are rather mixed.
Had the game not been mitigated by the aforementioned totally unnecessary errors, we could have argued with the chest tone of conviction that The Run is the best piece of NFS in recent years.
But that’s how the game seems unfinished.
A great pleasure for yourself, but you should be prepared to face these mistakes with the power of airport headlights.
