IBM History: From Cheese Cutter to World Flights
Founded a hundred years ago in New York City, IBM (International Business Machines) initially had a rather complicated name - Computing Tabulating Recording Corporation.
It was not until 1924 that IBM took over the name - originally it was a brand name for a branch in Canada and South America.
The cornerstone of IBM’s later company was the merger of four companies whose history dates back to the 80s of the 19th century.
They had technologies such as the famous flashcard clocks to register the start and end of work.
The architect of this new company was Charles Ranlett Flint, who also chaired the Supervisory Board until 1930.
And it was Flint who hired the head of the competition company Thomas J. Watson to help him run the company.
This leader then even put IBM’s founders in the shadows – based on Watson’s ideas to this day, the company’s invincible culture and identity.
Watson ran the company until 1952.
IBM, as the name suggests, began with the manufacture and distribution of all kinds of machines for trade - from sausage and cheese cutters to cash registers.
In the first four decades that Watson ran the company, he doubled its sales to $9 million and the company gradually expanded to all continents.
Watson was so indispensable to the company that he sat in the chief chair for forty years, only then was he replaced by his son, Thomas Watson Junior.
Under his leadership, IBM began working on the development of artificial intelligence and also developed the first programming language.
In the 1960s, IBM’s engineers and computers helped direct NASA’s flights into space – to Mercury and Saturn, and in 1969 also the famous human flight to the moon.
In 1964, IBM developed the first computer family with the same computer architecture – the IBM System/360 series.
A classic PC that set the computer standard of that time came on the market in 1981 under the name IBM 5150.
Twenty years later, IBM sold its computer production to the Chinese company Lenovo, but on the other hand, it bought the consulting part of the company PricewaterhouseCoopers and thus entered fully into the business of consulting services and services with high added value.
The strategy that IBM has been paying off over the past three years is the “Smarter Planet” concept.
It embodies the intention to use technologies wisely in areas not previously planned, for example, to improve the situation in traffic and in urban administration.
In the commercial sector, IBM recently introduced the “Smarter Commerce” platform, which is meant to help traders manage the entire commercial cycle.
IBM also has a strong history in the Czech Republic.
Already in 1932, IBM established a branch in the then-Czechoslovakia – as the first country in Central and Eastern Europe.
Today, IBM <0xC4><0x8C>R also operates a strategic outsourcing center in Brno.
The Centre for Central and Eastern Europe is based in Prague and here is also a top-level research team of world-class that deals with voice recognition technology.
