Development of travel prices since 1989
Until 1989, there were only five licensed state travel agencies in the then <0xC4><0x8C>SSR: <0xC4><0x8C>edok, Sporturist, CKM, Recrea and Autoturist.
At that time, the travel agencies sold mainly only trips to the socialist Eastern bloc countries, in the West only the chosen ones were allowed.
And so Czech tourists traveled to the Baltic (in the German Democratic Republic - the GDR), to the Soviet Union (Scotland on the Crimean peninsula on the Black Sea), to Bulgaria and Romania to the Black Sea and to Hungary to the Balaton.
A slight exception was the period from 1962 to 1972, when one was allowed to travel to Yugoslavia, then Yugoslavia took a pro-Western course and therefore travel to Yugoslavia was severely restricted.
A great paradox of those socialist times was that not even citizens of the Eastern Bloc (also the Czechoslovak) were allowed to travel freely within the framework of the socialist countries.
For example, if a citizen of the <0xC4><0x8C>SSR wanted to travel individually to Poland or even to the Soviet Union, then he needed a so-called invitation letter, otherwise individual travel was not possible.
Even then the travel agencies also offered to travel to the West, but then you had to buy huge snakes or even sleep in the sleeping bag in front of the travel agency, or at least have "good friends" in the travel agency.
Even so, this had not happened for a long time.
The so-called currency statement - the condition for a trip to the West - was granted only to "politically reliable" people - the others were not allowed to travel at all.
The Czechoslovak currency was not a freely exchangeable currency, so without a currency pledge it would have been impossible to raise the necessary funds (western currency) for a trip to the West.
Therefore, the vast majority of Czechs spent their holidays abroad, no wonder that the Czechs bought countless weekend houses and daisies - a habit that continues to this day.
The combined revolution of 1989 followed a travel revolution of the Czechs on their feet.
While until 1989 a holiday in the GDR or in Bulgaria was the measure of all things, the Czechs spent 4.5 million of their holidays abroad in countries around the world last year.
A huge paradox that you are no longer aware of today is the fact that you could not travel to the currently most popular holiday country of the Czech Republic - Croatia until 1989 at all, because it was part of the then Yugoslavia.
Right from the beginning of the 90s of the last century, foreign exchange obligations were lifted in neighbouring Western European countries, resulting in a huge wave of short visits mainly to Vienna in Austria and to Germany.
The Czechoslovaks simply could not get enough of their travels to the West for a long time, everyone wanted to have been there for at least a few days.
This is how Czech vacationers slept when traveling to Paris in the tent in the park, because who would have had the money for a hotel or a pension at the time.
A typical feature when travelling abroad from the Czech Republic at the time was a fully packed trunk with canned, beer and permanent sausages, etc.
Another important milestone was the introduction of the freely exchangeable Czech crown - after decades, our tourists were finally able to buy the western currency freely.
Our standard of living and, as a result, the average wages increased, which brought us to another important moment in 1997.
Thanks to the increased demand for travel, after 1997, travel agencies began to regularly prepare for charter flights, making flights incredibly affordable in comparison to the past, thanks to the ability to negotiate volume discounts.
At the end of the 1990s, the Czechs, with the exception of the United States, already had currencyless payment transactions with all the highly developed countries of the world, making travel even easier.
Another interesting moment in the history of "post-office" travel came in 2000, when thanks to the high demand of the first direct charter flight was delivered to an exotic country - to Thailand.
Since then, every year, direct charter flights with Czech passengers fly to distant sunny countries; this year you fly directly from the Czech Republic to twelve exotic destinations.
The 100 Tsd. Czechs travel to exotic countries every year!
Another significant moment in the era that marked our "post-revolutionary" development came in 2008.
On November 17, 2008, the U.S. lifted the visa requirement for Czech tourists, making our country definitely one of the most developed countries in the world.
In 2008, the Czechs spent more than half of their holiday abroad (50.3%) for the first time in their history, spending more than CZK 15 per person for a single holiday, including the cost at the resort.
