Six people said they were character-producers on behalf of the alleged perpetrator, who was eventually released.
“I still remember the day the verdict was read,” Lyman says.
"I thought the cries were going to be used, and I ran out of the courtroom screaming."
"They brought me to the psychiatric department and I remember when I came out again, I said to my commander, 'That wasn't his procedure. That was my procedure.'
Lyman was asked to visit a military psychiatrist who eventually diagnosed a personality disorder and declared her unfit for service.
In January 2010, she was unfairly fired, so she received no support whatsoever.
Whether the lawsuit that Lyman and the other plaintiffs filed is progressing is pure speculation, says John Turley, professor of law at George Washington University Law School.
However, he notes: "In my opinion, they should move forward."
What stands between them and a verdict is this doctrine, which has been criticized since it was first questioned.
I have always been a critic of the Feres Doctrine.
The military hangs back a decade, because they do not possess the same incentive and the same deterrence that a liability brings with them.
He adds, "The odds are against them... but it's important for them to try."
These things will only change when good people are ready to fight.
If the hearing does not follow her path, Burke, the plaintiff’s lawyer, will begin with her hundreds of other plaintiffs for future cases.
