Walls Have Eyes: How Researchers Watch You on Facebook
Before he became the new face of right-wing extremism in Europe, Anders Behring Breivik was just one of many guys who sent their anti-immigration opinion online.
On Monday, Breivik, who has confessed to having committed suicide in Norway in July, in which 77 people were killed, had his first public hearing in court.
Although Breivik may have acted alone, he is by no means alone in cyberspace: he spent a lot of time before his attack on his computer, shaming with some of the millions of nationalists who support far-right groups on social media sites.
After this summer’s tragedy, researchers wanted to find out more about these people.
But how do you find them?
It’s easy – you just have to log in to Facebook.
“We have found that it was not difficult to get to them,” says Jamie Bartlett, the lead author of a recently published report by the British think tank DEMOS on digital populism in Europe.
Facebook’s hiding of personal data is so encyclopedic, says Bartlett that researchers simply need to use the site’s advertising tool to accurately determine their desired demographic data with scientific accuracy – as marketers have been doing for years.
Bartlett’s team found half a million fans of far-right groups across Europe and then visited them with Adds, but instead of linking to a new band or diet product, the Adds users invited users to a survey in which, according to their educational status, their attitude towards violence and their savings, were spared.
Thanks to Facebook, Bartlett and his colleagues were able to poll more than 10,000 supporters from 14 far-right parties in 11 European countries – without even having to leave their office once.
“It’s a fairly new research method,” Bartlett says.
Some of the results hardly surprise. Online supporters of right-wing extremist groups are mostly young, male, and angry about immigration.
But in a kind of surprising twist, “those who combine their online activism with an offline activism are more reasonable, democratic and less violent than those who sit behind their computer screens.”
DEMO’s work is just an example of how Facebook becomes a new hot tool in the hands of scientists.
Idea factories, medical researchers and political scientists use the site to study everything from health issues to societal trends such as in "Likes", text messages and status updates.
With more than 800 million active users adding on average three content per day, Facebook’s “Data Supernova” is generating a research boom that has increased the number of scientific works named after this page in the title by almost 800 percent over the past five years.
For some researchers, the beauty of Facebook is the fact that through this site you can study people that you usually do not reach with their clipboard on the road.
"If you tried to question people of the British National Party earlier, it was very difficult to identify them."
"They had to inform the party first and they would never have granted them access," Bartlett said.
“With Facebook, all of this falls away – you go straight to them.”
Others say that the site offers a way to identify and solve social health problems.
A recent study by Dr. Megan Moreno of the University of Wisconsin, Madison, and her colleagues found that students who discussed their full-blown sound on Facebook were significantly more likely to drink problem drinks than students who were silent about this topic.
Moreno suggests that equivalent students, such as housing advisors, monitor the page and help a student when they post too many status updates.
“You can’t solve a problem if you don’t recognize it,” said Dimitri Christakis, co-author and director of Child Health, Behavior and Development at the Children’s Research Institute in Seattle, Washington Post.
“We have found a way to identify endangered children who would not otherwise have been found.”
Facebook is also constantly tapping into the data of its own population.
The site’s data team has created statistics on relationship status and Valentine’s Day, election participation in the 2010 midterm elections, and a National Happiness Index (primarily using data that only Facebook has access to – Masters of Digital Freedom knows for a long time that the site should make its big data pit for others to research).
However, Facebook users know that the site is watching them, whether they want to or not. In order to play Scrabble with a friend who is thousands of miles away, the site allows you to display your personal data.
But what if Facebook users become part of a survey they don’t even know anything about?
While researchers have strict guidelines on how to collect their data offline, everything is allowed online.
“I don’t think many users have even thought about the fact that a researcher could study their profiles,” says Neil Selwyn, a sociologist at the London Knowledge Lab, to a 2006 study in which he researched the public pages of students on Facebook.
“As far as she was concerned, it was just about her and her friends.”
Then there is the question of methodology.
Even offline there is no guarantee that a researcher is absolutely honest.
On Facebook, it is impossible to know how many of the information in a user profile and in posts are true.
“What you say on Facebook and what you do outside of Facebook are two completely different things,” Selwyn says.
Therefore, despite his years as a technology researcher, Selwyn believes that a clipboard and a pen are still the best research tools anyone can use.
“There is no substitute for going out into the real world and talking to real people,” he says.
“Social research needs to take care of social – and every lot of social life still takes place offline.”
