7 Lessons from an Interview with the Late Steve Jobs Showed at a Theater This Week
After the death of Steve Jobs on October 5, some compared him to Henry Ford, raising the technical genius as a great modern inventor.
But what Apple fans may find most revealing in the recently rediscovered job interview, which was dusted this week before special film screenings in key markets, is how much this creative head has understood business processes and workflows.
He was certainly a designer, a dreamer, and self-appointed hippie, but he was also an acribic organizer who worked eagerly on diagrams - a man who believed that many executives suffer from "a disease of thinking", "that a really great idea makes up a huge 90 percent of the work." [emphasis added]
In 1995, Bob Cringely developed the TV series "Triumph of the Professional Diodes" about the breakup of the personal computer, and he sat with jobs for more than an hour, in which they held one of the rare, detailed conversations.
By this time it had been more than 10 years since jobs had been pushed out of Apple, and he was already working hard at his new computer company NeXT, and was looking forward to the broad adoption of the Internet.
While a small portion of Cringley's interview was used in specialist diodes, he says that the interview's copy templates were missing from the delivery.
Only after Job’s death was a full VHS copy discovered in the director’s garage.
This slightly revised film material forms the basis for the 68-minute film "Steve Jobs: The Lost Interview", which comes to the Landmark Theater this Wednesday and Thursday.
For someone who is known to detest extensive interviews, Jobs here appears surprisingly eager to explain his technological philosophies and business strategies.
And incredibly thoughtful.
During the course of the interview, there are four times longer breaks between question and answer - 10 to 15 seconds in which jobs clearly weigh their thoughts and strive for accuracy.
There are also moments when Jobs' perfectionism comes to life when he seemingly impatiently responds to Cringely's questions and prompts him to deal more quickly with topics or side effects of greater importance.
Prior to the era of Pixar, iPod, or iPhone recording, the Lost Interview somehow seems unbelievably far-sighted when Jobs evaluates what other companies are doing right or wrong in his opinion and represents his own vision of the future of the computer.
It’s one thing to read posthumous appreciations of Jobs’ career, but seeing Jobs here as the eager dreamer who is on the jump to greatness is something completely different, original and inspiring.
He has a vision of how things could and should be.
Soon after he had done all of this, he left and did it.
A quick look at seven remarkable sequences of the Lost Interview:
How he learned to run a company:
"During all the years in business, I always ask, "Why do you do things?" And the answer you always get is, "Oh, that's how it's done."
Nobody knows why he's doing what he's doing. No one in the store really thinks about things in depth.
I've found that.
Jobs continues his efforts to streamline accounting at Apple.
Astonished by how costs were recorded - usually starting with "standard costs", which were denominated on mere guesses and then adjusted with "distinction" - he developed an automated factory that ensured that business costs could be determined to the minimum.
How the Pope was vilified:
Jobs tells of the "Blue Box" he built with Steve Wozniak, a device with which one could sneak into the phone company and conduct remote conversations for free.
Much has already been written about the device, but Jobs’ enthusiasm when he describes the Blue Box as an act of self-authorization is contagious.
He describes how Wozniak and he would test the box by using a pay phone, making a call, and then connecting from one AT&T network to another while looping through as many satellites as possible.
“We sent things half a dozen times around the globe, and when you rolled into the phone, it came out a minute later on the phone next door,” Jobs said.
“We were young and we learned that we can build something ourselves that can control trillions of dollars in infrastructure around the world.”
We both didn’t know much, but we were able to build this little thing that can control a giant thing, that was an incredible lesson and I don’t think there would be Apple without it.
Jobs goes on to tell of a glorious strike that Wozniak and he almost pulled off when they wanted to call in the middle of the night via Blue Box in the Vatican and talk to the Pope while they were able to imitate Henry Kissinger as well.
Since several members of the Catholic hierarchy were summoned in the middle of the night to speak with the American diplomat, the two had to laugh before the Pope himself came to the phone.
How he fell in love with the technique (and unprepared Bill Hewlett called):
At the age of 12, when he was looking for spare parts to build a frequency counter, he looked for Bill Hewlett in the phone book and called him.
Shortly after her 20-minute phone call, Jobs got a part-time job at Hewlett-Packard for the summer.
“It had a remarkable impact on me, it was the only company I had seen in my life and it shaped my views on what a company was and how well it treated its employees.”
Jobs later became one of the HP employees who visited the company’s research labs in Palo Alto, where he saw “the first desktop computer ever built.”
He was as big as a suitcase, had a small screen with Braunschweig tube and I fell in love with him.
I would climb up at HP as a teenager and hang onto this machine and write programs for them.
How to Improve Innovations:
Many times in the interview, Jobs talks about how to spontaneously invent new products.
Early in his career, when he installed some boards, he was asked by a customer to assemble the entire computer.
He worked with a payment period of only 30 days and had to think through both the assembly and delivery of the finished equipment.
Later at Apple, he recalls the problems he had with developing a computer mouse:
"I remember striking arguments... They yelled at me that it would take five years [to build a mouse that would cost $300] and I stood up, went out and found a manufacturer."
Ninety days later we had a mouse that we could build for $15. That was incredibly credible.
About large companies that rely on:
Long before he revived Apple, Jobs envisioned the ways in which so many industrial giants with their visions ran into stilts and lost control of their stocks.
“Let’s say you work at IBM or Xerox, so you’re making a better copywriter or printer, right?”
They own the stock monopoly, so the company is no longer successful.
Sales and marketing make it more successful, so [they are such people] who ultimately run the companies and the product with which people are pushed out of decision-making.
The product genius that has led to this monopoly position is needed by people who have no concept of good products vs. bad products, eradicated - craft art.
This happened at Xerox.
Xerox could have owned the entire computer industry.
One could have been ten times bigger, one could have been Microsoft in the 1990s...
You have won the victory.
About Innovation as an Art Form:
“It’s a lot of craftsmanship between a great idea and a great product... when you develop this great idea, it changes and grows.”
You learn a lot about their subtleties.
You have to make adjustments, certain things you can't do, but electrons, glass, robots, factories.
You have to remember 5,000 things, these concepts, and bring them all together...
In the end, it goes beyond taste, it goes beyond trying to mess up with the best thing people have created, and then trying to bring these things together to what you do.
Picasso said that good artists are copying, great artists are stealing.
We are always shameless in stealing great ideas.
Part of what made Macintosh great was that the people who worked there were musicians, poets, artists, zoologists, historians who happen to be the best computer scientists in the world.
Had it not been for the computer industry, they would have created fantastic things in other areas.
