The quintet embarked Costa Rica on its tour to celebrate its 20th anniversary
“Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true.”
In an exclusive interview with Viva, Pearl Jam bassist Jeff Ament says the band is prepared to give one of their best concerts at the National Stadium next Sunday.
They were expected for more than 20 years, but the band assures them that a dream will come true when they play in Costa Rica.
This was stated by the bassist and co-founder of the group, Jeff Ament, who gave Viva an exclusive interview from Brazil last week.
The band is in the South American part of their tour to celebrate their 20th anniversary and on Sunday, the 20th, they make their only stop in Central America.
On this day they will perform at the National Stadium starting at 7.30 pm together with the band The X from Los Angeles and Las Robertas from Costa Rica.
You can read an excerpt from the conversation whose full transcript can be found in the online edition of La Naci<0xC3><0xB3>n.
For your Costa Rican fans, a dream comes true when Pearl Jam plays in Costa Rica: Are you aware of what this means for your fans?
Playing in Costa Rica is a dream come true for us too.
This is just the second time we’ve played in South and Central America, and so far it’s been great.
I've only been to Costa Rica once for a holiday. It's such a beautiful country that we will definitely stay there for a few more days.
It is exciting for us to bring our music there.
I'm asking you this because the fans of the band are completely committed, and you're experiencing the days before the concert most intensively.
What do you think of your most enthusiastic fans?
Thank you for being with us all these years.
We took almost 21 years to get to Costa Rica. Thank you for waiting so long and we are sorry to have taken so long to get here.
Some people even think that your concert will be the biggest show of the year.
Isn’t that a bit of pressure from your visit?
Some of the greatest shows we’ve done in the last 21 years have taken place in the last two weeks.
We played on a couple of giant shows in Sao Paulo and we hope they made us fit for this concert in Costa Rica.
Really, we want to play there.
We love this country, we like to surf and are enthusiastic about the jungle. For that, Costa Rica belongs to the best countries in the world.
How did you get to know Costa Rica and its waves for surfing?
Many of our friends are surfers and I have a great friend who lives in Tamarindo, where the waves are simply unimaginable.
My friends have always gone to surf to Costa Rica and Nicaragua. Together with Mexico are the excellent areas to surf. In this way, we have learned about people who love surfing.
With a view of the tour, you have offered huge shows with many songs.
What are your plans for the event in Costa Rica?
Since we’ve never played there, we don’t set any limits.
We will try to give the best possible show with many different songs. We want to play a few songs from each album and offer our fans a good and versatile repertoire.
You will never repeat your repertoire.
Why?
I think that’s partly because we have nine records and can play over 120 songs, and everyone likes a different song, so the decision we’re going to play in each one is not easy.
If we record two or three songs that we have not played in the repertoire for a long time, we can better maintain our concentration and they surprise us because they remind us of the reasons why we liked these songs, otherwise they might be forgotten.
This makes the show more interesting for us and I think, therefore also for the audience.
With this tour, you celebrate your twenty-year history.
If you look back, is it hard for you to believe in your success?
Yeah, totally.
First of all, I don’t think any of us ever imagined playing in a great rock band, even for over 20 years, which seems like a dream.
We also continue to rely on these blessings and find it great to be able to make music together even now.
We love and are excited to bring out music.
We are lucky to be able to drive to the places of the world that we have always wanted to visit.
Things couldn't be better.
What did it mean for you to have actively participated in the birth hour of the grunge?
It has always been an honor to be part of this group of great bands.
We are good friends with the people of Soundgarden, Mudhoney and Alice in Chains.
It is surprising and quite unusual when a movement emerges from a group of friends.
Every now and then a band emerges from a city, but it is already unusual when five or ten groups come from the same city at the same time.
We are proud of it and feel honored to be part of the Seattle Group.
Sometimes we still play together.
Last year we were at a festival with Alice in Chains and in Canada with Mudhoney and we saw Soundgarden on their tour. We’re still looking forward to being friends with them all and it’s our honor to be part of this upcoming Seattle sound.
It is also very unusual for a band like yours to have stayed with the same musicians for so long.
Yes, four of us have been playing together for 21 years and Matt (Cameron) came to us 13 years ago. That alone is much more time than many bands can survive.
First of all, I think we all appreciate being alive and also taking care of each other.
We are all close friends, which is why musical ways have opened up that give each individual the freedom to experiment.
One is familiar with the other and his music, and we couldn't do any better.
Your relationship with fame has not always been easy, but on the other hand, thanks to your success, you have always been able to do what you want.
How do you find a balance?
The way we have grown has made it easier for us to find a balance.
We make sure not to be on tour too often, because it is too easy to fall for this game with huge crowds who love your music.
As long as you think that people came because of the music, it reminds you that you have to pay attention to the music and what brought it to life, without eating it being a famous rock star.
What memories do you have of your other project Mother Love Bone?
I think we wrote very good songs and in the beginning it was great.
We were a band for three years that never released a record until the death of Andy (Andrew Woods).
We were disappointed to have used it for so long. We are still good friends with Bruce (Fairweather) and Greg (Gilmore), who built the band with us. When I hear a song or photos, I think of what it was like to be a great person Andy and how he used to make me laugh, always making fun.
He was an extraordinary person and we miss him.
The domestic band Las Robertas is responsible for the opening of the show in Costa Rica.
Is it true that you know their work, especially Eddie Vedder, and that's why you chose the band for the opening?
Yes, the production sent us videos from several groups and this band liked us best. That’s why we are curious to see what Las Robertas can offer live. This will be exciting.
Why do you change the text of Yellow Ledbetter every time you play live?
This is a question for Ed (Eddie Vedder), I have no idea.
He sings him, and I think he sings the first thing that comes to his mind.
Who were you influenced by as a bassist?
Of so many+
Among the first to come to mind are Geezer Butler, John Entwistle, C. J. Ramone, John Doe, Paul McCartney, Chuck Dukowski...
There are so many that I could talk all afternoon about the bassists I like.
How did Pearl Jam manage to keep the grunge alive, even though it is no longer a fashion appearance?
I don't think we all feel very connected to the word grunge.
When I think about it, I like the bands I mentioned before, like Mudhoney, Soundgarden, Nirvana and everyone else who came up at the same time. If they are still important today, I find it great, because it’s worth listening to this music and bands like Mudhoney now make better music than ever.
In the beginning her music was darker, now she is more positive.
Why?
That’s interesting, because I think there are a few songs on the new album that might seem a bit easy, but there are also other songs like The End or Just Breathe that are classified as very dark songs, although they also have some positives in themselves.
Both of them came to me with tears when I heard Ed playing them, they're very dark songs.
I believe that when you get older and something traumatic has happened in your life – for example, when you lose a family member or a friend – that influences your artistic creation and your music and these two songs clearly embody that for me.
But I also believe that you can be a happy person and still make dark music.
