Asphalt from UNAM prevents impact holes
Rafael Herrera, researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry at the University of Mexico UNAM develops modified asphalt with polymers to make the mixture more resistant to weather conditions and temperature fluctuations
If the signs are taken care of or taken care of by the road cover, it would not be necessary to repair almost 200,000 impact holes if the rainy season breaks out in the zone Metropolitana del Valle de México (city area of the valley of Mexico), said Rafael Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera, the researcher at the Faculty of Chemistry (University of Asbestos)
In his lecture "Technical impact holes", which he held on the occasion of the International Year of Chemistry, he announced that the laboratory for which he is responsible is developing modified asphalts with polymers to produce a mixture similar to asphalt, which, however, do not have a greater mechanical resistance at both temperatures.
Herrera N<0xC3><0xA1>jera believed that this type of modified asphalt should be used in areas with extremely hot climates, such as in some cities in the north of the country, to improve the behavior of road surfaces and thus avoid the appearance of impact holes.
He explained that the asphalt - the heaviest part of the oil - is a hydrocarbon compound, of which one part has a high molecular weight - the so-called asphalts - and the other part a low - the so-called malthenes.
The static behavior of the asphalt means that it behaves like a liquid at high temperatures of almost 180<0xC2><0xB0> C., at 120<0xC2><0xB0> C. it is very densely liquid and almost solid at 50<0xC2><0xB0> C., while it becomes fragile at very low temperatures.
"This means that the resistance of asphalt on the roads is not uniform, but changes in a day depending on the weather conditions and temperature fluctuations," he said.
The FQ researcher noted that the streets of Mexico City mostly had a flexible road covering consisting of six layers of material, the last three of which contained asphalt.
Among the top layers is a layer of wear made of asphalt, which consists of small stones bathed in asphalt and then solidified.
Every single stone of this wear layer has been bathed in asphalt.
If the vehicles move on and forces are generated, this layer allows for a good distribution of forces in the road surface.
"If it were modified asphalt, the forces would be even better distributed," the chemical engineer said.
"Over the wear layer," he explained, "is designed a last layer, the so-called support layer, which consists of tiny stones, i.e. of sand, which was also bathed in asphalt.
Since this layer is in contact with the vehicle tires, they need a greater mechanical force than the wear layer and they need to produce friction.
This road covering receives and distributes most of the forces, the support layer also needs an appropriate thickness and the material from which it consists must be maintained.
The weather conditions, in particular humidity and temperature fluctuations, are other, important factors to consider, especially water," he said, "because it significantly affects the behavior of the wear layer.
When the terrain is wet, water enters the layer and only returns to a difficult position, causing all layers of the road surface to soften and, as a result, the appearance of impact holes.
When a blowhole occurs, "the cover layer is first removed, while the wear layer is only then damaged, but the damage does not occur immediately, but it is a process that must be maintained at the first signs by appropriate maintenance programs."
The member of the Sistema Nacional de Investigadores (National Research System of Mexico) explained that the vehicle load is another important cause for the occurrence of impact holes. Therefore, the thickness of each layer of the road surface must always be in relation to the vehicle load and it must be ensured that this impact will be avoided.
Rafael Herrera pointed out that a lot of research work had yet to be done, for example on asphalt emulsions, which were already on the market in other countries, and with which the impact holes could be repaired easily and without the use of high temperatures.
