Why does the unemployment rate of disabled workers remain at such a high level?
About 19% of people with disabilities are looking for a job.
Today begins the "15th week of work for the disabled".
Despite a deliberate public policy that was introduced in 2005, the unemployment rate for persons with disabilities is always twice as high as the average: 19% versus 9% of the total population.
Disgusting?
"No, so emphasizes <0xC3><0x89>ric Blanchet, Director General of the Adapt Association, which organizes the "Work Week for the Disabled."
"The progress made within fifteen years is considerable."
"At the time, the unemployment rate was not twice as high, but three times as high."
"Nevertheless, there is still a lot to do."
However, it must be said that for the disabled, many obstacles continue to exist before they get a job.
The elderly are more common: 37% are older than 50 years (17% on average).
They have a low level of qualification: 80% of them do not have an undergraduate degree and there are only 10,000 disabled among the 2.3 million students with a higher education degree.
Finally, long-term unemployment is also very widespread: 53% of the disabled compared to 38% in total.
In short, there are so many criteria that make it difficult to get back to work and that form the “core of the problem,” says Christian Grapin, Director General of Tremplin, an association founded in 1992 that helps companies to recruit disabled workers.
So much for the brakes.
Remains the unspoken, the attitudes of the mind, which, though certain, but slowly develop.
A study conducted in April by the IMS-entreprendre association for La Cité magazine stated that the managers surveyed had "a weak level of knowledge regarding the disabled", which was "overrepresented" "by persons in wheelchairs, mentally or intellectually disabled".
As a result, private companies with more than 20 employees still have a long way to go to achieve the employment target of 6% of disabled workers, which was set out in a 1987 law.
These last-mentioned figures, from 2008, refer to a quotient of 2.6%.
“We are now at 3%,” said Pierre Blanc, CEO of Agefiph, the organization that is charged with soliciting contributions from companies that are violating this law.
The evidence: The number of "fees paid" establishments has decreased as well as the sum of the amounts paid between 2007 and 2011, from 59,000 to 46,000 (and from 606 to 480 million euros).
“The 2005 law, which provides for increases in contributions, created a strong pressure on companies,” explained Pierre Blanc.
"But this improvement also brings out a real insight, especially in the large corporate groups."
According to the Ministry of Labour, only 59% of the workplaces between 20 and 49 employees are disabled workers, while companies with 100 to 199 employees employ 82%.
